","Beauchamp Court, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Calvados, Normandie, Frankrijk","Beauchamp, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk","Ile-de-France, France":"Île-de-France, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1020–1058":"1020–1058","1022–1066":"1022–1066","1022–1081":"1022–1081","1040–1114":"1040–1114","1040–Male":"1040–Deceased","1060–Female":"1060–Deceased","1007–1068":"1007–1068","0990–Female":"0990–Deceased","about 1040":"about 1040","1066":"1066","1022":"1022","1020":"1020","1040":"1040","1094":"1094","1060":"1060","1081":"1081","1007":"1007","1114":"1114","1058":"1058","0990":"0990","1068":"1068","before 1040":"before 1040","Abbaye de Saint-Pierre de Préaux, Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Bithaine, Haute-Saône, Franche-Comté, France":"Haute-Saône, Franche-Comté, France","Beauchamp Court, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Calvados, Normandy, France","Beauchamp, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","Ile-de-France, France":"Île-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Beauchamp was born in 1020, in Calvados, Lower Normandy, France, his father, Walter de Beauchamp, was 13 and his mother, Bertha de Braose, was 31. He married Adeliuza Alix de Meulan before 1040, in Île-de-France, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1058, in Haute-Saône, Franche-Comté, France, at the age of 38, and was buried in Normandy, France."},"et":{"1020–1058":"1020–1058","1022–1066":"1022–1066","1022–1081":"1022–1081","1040–1114":"1040–1114","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","1060–Female":"1060–Surnud","1007–1068":"1007–1068","0990–Female":"0990–Surnud","about 1040":"umbes 1040","1066":"1066","1022":"1022","1020":"1020","1040":"1040","1094":"1094","1060":"1060","1081":"1081","1007":"1007","1114":"1114","1058":"1058","0990":"0990","1068":"1068","before 1040":"enne 1040","Abbaye de Saint-Pierre de Préaux, Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Bithaine, Haute-Saône, Franche-Comté, France":"Haute-Saône, Franche-Comté, Prantsusmaa","Beauchamp Court, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Beauchamp, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Ile-de-France, France":"Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1020–1058":"1020–1058","1022–1066":"1022–1066","1022–1081":"1022–1081","1040–1114":"1040–1114","1040–Male":"1040–Kuollut","1060–Female":"1060–Kuollut","1007–1068":"1007–1068","0990–Female":"0990–Kuollut","about 1040":"noin 1040","1066":"1066","1022":"1022","1020":"1020","1040":"1040","1094":"1094","1060":"1060","1081":"1081","1007":"1007","1114":"1114","1058":"1058","0990":"0990","1068":"1068","before 1040":"ennen vuotta 1040","Abbaye de Saint-Pierre de Préaux, Normandie, France":"Normandie, Ranska","Bithaine, Haute-Saône, Franche-Comté, France":"Haute-Saône, Franche-Comté, Ranska","Beauchamp Court, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Calvados, Nor